```javascript
function isPrime(num) {
  if (num <= 1) return false; // 0 and 1 are not primes
  if (num <= 3) return true;  // 2 and 3 are primes

  // Eliminate even numbers and multiples of 3 early
  if (num % 2 === 0 || num % 3 === 0) return false;

  // Check from 5 to the square root of num
  for (let i = 5; i * i <= num; i += 6) {
    if (num % i === 0 || num % (i + 2) === 0) return false;
  }

  return true;
}

function checkPrimes(arr) {
  if (arr.length !== 5) {
    console.log("Input array must contain exactly 5 numbers.");
    return;
  }

  arr.forEach(num => {
    if (isPrime(num)) {
      console.log(`Number ${num} is a prime number.`);
    }
  });
}

// Example usage:
const numbers = [10, 3, 7, 11, 19];
checkPrimes(numbers); // This will print: Number 3 is a prime number. and Number 7 is a prime number. etc.
```

### Explanation:
1. **`isPrime(num)` Function**:
   - Handles edge cases for numbers less than or equal to 3.
   - Eliminates even numbers and multiples of 3 quickly.
   - Uses a loop to check divisibility from 5 up to the square root of the number, incrementing by 6 (to skip even numbers and multiples of 3).

2. **`checkPrimes(arr)` Function**:
   - Validates the input array length (ensures exactly 5 numbers).
   - Iterates through the array, using `isPrime` to check each number.
   - Prints the prime numbers found.

You can test the function with different arrays to see how it identifies prime numbers.

